<dl id="n05062e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05062e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05062e"> 62(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> just recognisable</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> So the baby has longer time to store up his impressions and continue his experiments, until by trying again and again he at length gets his lesson learnt in all its tiny details, while the man in the foreign country, who must make himself understood, as a rule goes on trying only till he has acquired a form of speech which he finds natives understand: at this point he will generally stop, at any rate as far as pronunciation and the construction of sentences are concerned (while his vocabulary may be largely increased). But this &ldquo;<mark>just recognizable</mark>&rdquo; language is incorrect in thousands of small details, and, inasmuch as bad little habits quickly become fixed, the kind of language is produced which we know so well in the case of resident foreigners&mdash;who need hardly open their lips before everyone knows they are not natives, and before a practiced ear can detect the country they <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJLN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJLN"><cite title="source">Language: its Nature, Development and Origin</cite></a> (Jan 1922) 145</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
